## ⚡ 3. Growth Drivers

### 3.1 🤖 AI & Generative AI Infrastructure Demand

GenAI is the **single most transformative demand driver** for data center infrastructure since the birth of cloud computing.

```
Traditional Compute Rack Density  →   5 – 15 kW/rack
AI / GPU Cluster Rack Density     →  30 – 80 kW/rack   (5–10x increase)
Next-Gen AI Factory Density       →  80 – 120+ kW/rack
```

**Key Impacts:**
- Complete rethinking of cooling architecture, power distribution, and structural loading
- Shift to **liquid cooling**, rear-door heat exchangers (RDHx), and direct liquid cooling (DLC)
- Hyperscaler AI investment (Amazon + Microsoft + Google + Meta): **exceeded $200B collectively in 2024–2025**
- GPU server clusters require purpose-built facilities with **100+ MW campus-scale power**

<br>

### 3.2 ☁️ Cloud Computing Expansion

| Year | Enterprise Cloud Adoption |
|------|--------------------------|
| 2020 | ~20–25% penetration |
| 2026 | **~60%+** *(mid-to-large enterprises)* |

AWS · Microsoft Azure · Google Cloud continue expanding globally at an accelerating pace. SaaS, PaaS, and IaaS models drive **continuous demand** for new capacity.

<br>

### 3.3 📶 Edge Computing, Low Latency & 5G

Edge data centers (sub-1 MW to 5 MW, within 20–50 km of end-users) serve latency-sensitive applications that centralized hyperscale facilities cannot efficiently support:

- Autonomous vehicles · Smart manufacturing · Real-time video analytics
- Augmented reality (AR) · Industrial IoT · Gaming

**Edge Market Growth:**
```
2021:  $7.2B  ──────────────────────────────────────► 2026:  $19.1B – $22.2B
                              CAGR ~22%
```

<br>

### 3.4 🔄 Digital Transformation

Healthcare digitization · Fintech (real-time payments, fraud detection) · E-commerce · Media streaming · Government digital services — all requiring scalable, reliable compute infrastructure. The secular shift from on-premises to colocation and cloud has made data centers an **essential utility of the modern economy**.

---

## 💰 4. Financial Analysis

### 4A. Construction Costs — CapEx

> **Industry Benchmark: $7M – $12M per MW of IT load capacity**  
> AI-optimized high-performance facilities: $15M – $20M+ per MW

<br>

#### Component Breakdown

| CapEx Component | % of Total | Cost per MW | Notes |
|----------------|-----------|-------------|-------|
| Land & Site Development | 8–12% | $0.6M – $1.4M | Location, zoning, site prep |
| Civil / Structural Works | 10–15% | $0.8M – $1.7M | Foundation, shell, raised floors |
| **Power Infrastructure** | **30–40%** | **$2.5M – $4.5M** | Switchgear, UPS, generators, PDUs |
| **Cooling Systems** | **20–30%** | **$1.6M – $3.2M** | CRAC/CRAH, chillers, DLC |
| IT Hardware (Shell) | 5–10% | $0.5M – $1.0M | Racks, cabling (excl. servers) |
| Fire Suppression & Safety | 3–5% | $0.2M – $0.5M | FM200/Novec, VESDA |
| Security & BMS Systems | 2–4% | $0.15M – $0.4M | DCIM, BMS, CCTV, access |
| Fit-Out & Commissioning | 5–8% | $0.4M – $0.8M | MEP install, testing, commissioning |

<br>

#### Hyperscale vs. Edge vs. Mid-Scale

| Parameter | Hyperscale (100+ MW) | Mid-Scale (5–20 MW) | Edge (<1 MW) |
|-----------|---------------------|-------------------|-------------|
| **CapEx per MW** | $7M – $10M | $9M – $12M | $12M – $20M+ |
| Build Timeline | 18–36 months | 12–24 months | 6–12 months |
| Power Density | 8–15 kW/rack | 10–30 kW/rack | 20–50 kW/rack |
| PUE Target | 1.1 – 1.3 | 1.2 – 1.4 | 1.3 – 1.5 |
| Economies of Scale | Very High | Moderate | Low |
| Cooling Strategy | Evaporative / DLC | Air / Hybrid | Air / Rear-door |

---

### 4B. Operating Costs — OpEx

> **Power = 40–60% of total annual OpEx** — the dominant cost variable in any DC project

<br>

#### Annual OpEx Breakdown (Per MW IT Load)

| OpEx Category | % of OpEx | Annual Cost/MW | Key Variable |
|--------------|----------|---------------|-------------|
| **Power — IT Load** | **35–45%** | **$0.8M – $1.4M** | PUE, electricity tariff |
| Power — Cooling Overhead | 10–15% | $0.2M – $0.5M | PUE efficiency, climate |
| Cooling System Maintenance | 5–8% | $0.1M – $0.25M | Chiller/HVAC service contracts |
| Staffing & Operations | 10–15% | $0.2M – $0.4M | NOC, security, FM team |
| Network & Connectivity | 8–12% | $0.15M – $0.3M | Transit, cross-connects |
| Maintenance (Civil/MEP) | 5–8% | $0.1M – $0.2M | Preventive / corrective |
| Insurance & Compliance | 2–4% | $0.04M – $0.1M | ISO, Tier certification |
| Management & G&A | 3–5% | $0.06M – $0.12M | Overhead allocation |

<br>

#### ⚡ Power Usage Effectiveness (PUE)

> **PUE = Total Facility Power ÷ IT Equipment Power**  
> Lower is better. PUE 1.0 = perfect efficiency (theoretical maximum).

| PUE | Classification | Cooling Strategy | Waste (per 10 MW) |
|-----|---------------|-----------------|------------------|
| **1.1 – 1.2** | **World Class** | Direct liquid, adiabatic | ~1–2 MW |
| 1.2 – 1.4 | Efficient / Modern | Chilled water, economizers | ~2–4 MW |
| 1.4 – 1.6 | Average / Industry Mean | CRAC, hot aisle containment | ~4–6 MW |
| 1.6 – 2.0 | Below Average / Legacy | Legacy HVAC, no containment | ~6–10 MW |

---

### 4C. Revenue Model

| Revenue Stream | Pricing Model | Rate Range | Margin Profile |
|---------------|--------------|-----------|---------------|
| **Retail Colocation** | Per rack / per kW / per sqft | $800 – $2,500+/rack/month | 55–65% gross |
| **Hyperscale Wholesale** | Per kW, long-term (10–15 yr) | $80 – $130/kW/month | 45–55% gross |
| **Interconnection** | Per cross-connect port | $150 – $600+/port/month | **60–80% EBITDA** |
| **Edge Managed Services** | Bundled contracts, SLA premium | 30–50% premium over colo | 50–60% gross |

---

### 4D. Profitability Analysis

| Metric | Hyperscale Wholesale | Retail Colocation | Edge Deployment |
|--------|---------------------|------------------|----------------|
| Revenue per kW/month | $80 – $130 | $150 – $250+ | $200 – $400+ |
| Gross Margin | 45 – 55% | 55 – 65% | 50 – 60% |
| **EBITDA Margin** | **40 – 50%** | **45 – 55%** | **40 – 50%** |
| Target IRR | 10 – 14% | 12 – 18% | 14 – 20% |
| Payback Period | 10 – 15 years | 8 – 12 years | 6 – 10 years |
| Contract Term | 10 – 20 years | 3 – 5 years | 5 – 10 years |

